{"id":"6773","name":"Get System Language [JS1]","tagline":"A JavaScript one-liner to find out the language of your device","icon":"ios12 c255 g59412","latest":"21387","description":"\n\t\t\t\t\t<p>A single line of JavaScript to find out what language your system uses*. This is somewhat slower than my <a href=\"https://routinehub.co/shortcut/2981/\">System Language</a> shortcut, but its simplicity is unbeatable.</p>\n<ul>\n<li>No error checking</li>\n<li><a href=\"https://editor.scpl.dev/?scpl=%40Icon%20globe%0A%40Color%20darkgray%0AComment%20%22A%20JavaScript%20one-liner%20to%20find%20out%20the%20system%20language%20configured%20in%20your%20device%20%E2%80%94%20%40atnbueno%20(2020-10-02)%5Cn%5Cn-%20This%20is%20slightly%20slower%20than%20my%20%5C%22System%20Language%5C%22%20shortcut%2C%20but%20its%20simplicity%20is%20unbeatable%5Cn-%20No%20error%20checking%22%0AURL%20%22data%3Atext%2Fhtml%2C%3Cscript%3Edocument.write(navigator.language.substr(0%2C2))%3C%2Fscript%3E%22%0AGetFileofType%20%22com.apple.webarchive%22%20-%3E%20mv%3A%22Get%20File%20of%20Type%22%0AShowResult%20mv%3A%22Get%20File%20of%20Type%22%7Bas%3A%20text%7D\">ScPL source</a></li>\n<li><a href=\"https://developer.mozilla.org/en-US/docs/Web/API/NavigatorLanguage/language\"><code>NavigatorLanguage.language</code> documentation at MDN</a></li>\n</ul>\n<p>(*) Thanks to <a href=\"https://routinehub.co/user/arifbuti\">@arifbuti</a> (see feedback below) I found out that the Shortcuts app has its own language setting (at least in iOS 14), and that's what this shortcut normally detects. To detect the <em>real</em> system language you must run this snippet from an automation.</p>\n<h4>Don't download the shortcut</h4>\n<p>If you just want the code, there's no need to download the shortcut. Copy this and paste it in a \"URL\" action:</p>\n<pre><code>data:text/html,&lt;script&gt;document.write(navigator.language.substr(0,2))&lt;/script&gt;\n</code></pre>\n\n<p>Add a \"Get File of Type\" with type <code>com.apple.webarchive</code> below, and its output will be the <a href=\"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/List_of_ISO_639-1_codes\">two-letter ISO 639 language code</a> (e.g. \"en\" for English, and \"es\" for Spanish).</p>\n<p>I use \"Get File of Type\" instead of \"Get Contents of Webpage\" to avoid that the user is misleading told that the shortcut uses Safari.</p>\n\t\t\t\t","releasenotes":"<p><strong>1.0.0 - Oct. 2, 2020, 2:03 a.m.</strong></p>"}